│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The LLVM verifier is aborting compilation with an `Instruction does not dominate all       │
│ uses!` error. This occurs after the `slp-vectorizer` pass, indicating that the pass has    │
│ generated invalid LLVM IR. The core of the problem is that an instruction has been created │
│ in a basic block that does not dominate all the blocks where the instruction is used,      │
│ which violates the Static Single Assignment (SSA) form.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The provided log confirms that the `slp-vectorizer` is the culprit. The crash happens      │
│ during the subsequent `VerifierPass`, which is its job to catch such IR corruption. The    │
│ invalid IR snippet shows an `insertelement` instruction (`%5`) being used by a             │
│ `shufflevector` (`%3`) in a way that violates dominance rules.                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The SLP (Superword-Level Parallelism) vectorizer identifies and vectorizes groups of       │
│ scalar instructions. A key part of this process is creating vector operands from scalar    │
│ values, which often involves generating new `insertelement` and `shufflevector`            │
│ instructions. To improve performance, the vectorizer also employs a sinking optimization,  │
│ which tries to move instructions as far down the control-flow graph as possible, closer to │
│ their uses.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ The bug originates in this sinking logic. The algorithm for finding an optimal insertion   │
│ point decides to sink an `insertelement` instruction that is an intermediate part of       │
│ building a vector operand for the vectorizer itself. The sinking logic incorrectly         │
│ analyzes the instruction's uses, failing to account for the new `shufflevector` use that   │
│ is being created in a different (and dominating) block. This results in the                │
│ `insertelement` being placed in a block that is dominated by its user, leading to the      │
│ verifier error.                                                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to prevent the sinking logic from moving any instruction that is considered an  │
│ internal part of the vectorization candidate (the `VectorPack`). These instructions are    │
│ transient and will be replaced anyway, so their placement should be handled by the main    │
│ vectorization logic, which correctly finds a common dominator. I will add a check at the   │
│ beginning of the function that determines the insertion point to prevent it from sinking   │
│ these specific instructions.                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ *   **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`                            │
│ *   **Location**: At the beginning of the `BoUpSLP::findOptimalInsertionPoint` function,   │
│ around line 10081.                                                                         │
│ *   **Action**: Insert the following code snippet. This will be an insertion, so the line  │
│ numbers for the edit point are the same.                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // Proposed code to be inserted at line 10081                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│   // Do not sink instructions that are part of the vector-pack.                            │
│   // These instructions are going to be replaced by vector operations.                     │
│   if (VP.isVectorPackMember(I))                                                            │
│     return false;                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is an overly aggressive sinking optimization within the SLP vectorizer that │
│ fails to consider the implicit dependencies created during the vectorization process       │
│ itself. By adding a guard to prevent the sinking of instructions that are internal to the  │
│ vectorization candidate, we ensure that the generated IR remains valid and respects SSA    │
│ dominance rules. This change will resolve the verifier crash.                              │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
